4.2.3 Classification Loss. SE-GNN is expected to give accurate pre-

dictions. Therefore, we utilize the supervision from the given labels

to ensure the accuracy of the self-explainable GNN. One straight-

forward way is to optimize the predictions of nodes with labels

in a leave-one-out manner. More specifically, for a labeled node ğ‘£ğ‘– âˆˆ Vğ¿, we identify ğ¾-nearest labeled nodes from other labeled nodes Vğ¿ âˆ’ {ğ‘£ğ‘– }. Then loss such as cross entropy loss can be applied to optimize the model. However, in this way, the optimization only

involves the searched ğ¾-nearest neighbors which are generally

similar nodes. Lacking of various negative samples may negatively

affect similarity modeling. In addition, the computational cost to

identify ğ¾-nearest neighbors will be large when numerous labeled

nodes are given. To address these issues, we propose a loss function

that adopts negative sampling [23] and approximately select ğ¾-

nearest labeled nodes as positive samples. Specifically, for a target node ğ‘£ğ‘¡ âˆˆ Vğ¿, we randomly sample ğ‘„ labeled nodes Vğ‘›ğ‘¡ which do not share the same label with ğ‘£ğ‘¡ as negative samples. And we

randomly sample ğ‘ (ğ‘ > ğ¾) labeled nodes sharing the same la-

bel with ğ‘£ğ‘¡ as support set to obtain approximate ğ¾-nearest labeled nodes KËœğ‘¡ . The objective function can be formally written as:

