where eğ‘– denotes a query edge representation, and eËœ+ is the positive sample from dictionary {eËœ0, ..., eËœğ‘„ğ¸ }. With the self-supervision, the
representations of similar edges and nodes will be similar, which

can facilitate the similarity modeling for explanations. Moreover,

since edge perturbation is used to augment the graph in contrastive

learning, the representations from the perturbed graph will be

enforced to be consistent with the representations from the clean

graph. This will lead to robustness against structure noise.

4.4 Overall Objective Function

With the supervision from the labels for accurate prediction, and the contrastive learning on node and edge representations to facilitate the modeling of similarity, the final loss function of SE-GNN is:

min Lğ‘ + ğ›¼ Lğ‘› + ğ›½Lğ‘’,

(14)

ğœƒ

where ğœƒ represents the parameters of SE-GNN. ğ›¼ and ğ›½ are hyperparameters that control the contributions of self-supervision on node similarity modeling and edge matching in local similarity evaluation, respectively.

4.5 Training Algorithm and Time Complexity
4.5.1 Training Algorithm. The training algorithm of SE-GNN is given in Algorithm 1. In line 1, the parameters of SE-GNN are randomly initialized with Xavier initialization [11]. In line 3, the

Algorithm 1: Training Algorithm of SE-GNN. Input: G = (V, E, X) , Y, ğ¾, ğ›¼, ğ›½, ğœ†, ğœ. Output: Self-explainable GNN ğ‘“G. 1: Randomly initialize the parameters of ğ‘“G. 2: repeat 3: Obtain the classification loss by Eq.(11) 4: Augment the G with attribute masking and edge perturbation to receive graphs in different views 5: Sample a node batch Vğµ with positive and negative pairs 6: Calculate contrastive loss on nodes by Eq.(12) 7: Sample an edge batch Eğµ with positive and negative pairs 8: Get contrastive loss on edges by Eq.(13) 9: Optimize the parameter of ğ‘“G by Eq.(14) 10: until convergence 11: return ğ‘“G
supervised loss from the labeled nodes is calculated. Graph augmentation is conducted in line 4, which gives graphs in different views for contrastive learning. From line 5 to line 9, contrastive losses for nodes and edges are computed. For the size of negative samples in Eq.(11), it is fixed as 20. The sizes of negative samples in Eq.(12) and Eq.(13) are both set as 100 during the training phase.
4.5.2 Time Complexity. During the test phase, the main time complexity comes from the similarity scores calculation between the test node ğ‘£ğ‘¡ and all the labeled nodes Vğ¿. For each node ğ‘£ğ‘™ âˆˆ Vğ¿, the cost for calculating the edge matching with ğ‘£ğ‘¡ is O (ğ‘‘ Â· |Eğ‘¡ | Â· |Eğ‘™ |), where ğ‘‘ is the embedding dimension. Thus, the time complexity for one test node is approximately O (ğ‘‘ Â· |Eğ‘¡ | Â· ğ‘£ğ‘™ âˆˆVğ¿ |Eğ‘™ |). As for the training phase, we adopt a sampling strategy in Eq.(11) to reduce the pairs of similarity to be computed. For each node ğ‘£ğ‘¡ âˆˆ Vğ¿, let Sğ‘¡ = Kğ‘¡ âˆª Vğ‘›ğ‘¡ denotes the sampled positive and negative nodes in Eq.(11), the cost of calculating classification loss for ğ‘£ğ‘¡ is O (ğ‘‘ Â· |Eğ‘¡ | Â· ğ‘£ğ‘™ âˆˆSğ‘¡ Â·|Eğ‘™ |). Thus, the cost for classification loss of all labeled nodes is O ( ğ‘£ğ‘¡ âˆˆVğ‘¡ ğ‘£ğ‘™ âˆˆSğ‘¡ ğ‘‘ Â· |Eğ‘¡ | Â· |Eğ‘™ |).With the computation cost on contrastive learning, the overall time complexity for an iteration in the training phase is O (ğ‘‘ Â· (ğ‘„ğ‘› |Vğµ | + ğ‘„ğ‘’ |Eğµ | +
ğ‘£ğ‘¡ âˆˆVğ‘¡ ğ‘£ğ‘™ âˆˆSğ‘¡ |Eğ‘¡ | Â· |Eğ‘™ |)).
5 EXPERIMENTS
In this section, we conduct extensive experiments on real-world and synthetic datasets to demonstrate the effectiveness of SE-GNN. In particular, we aim to answer the following research questions:
â€¢ RQ1 Can our proposed method simultaneously provide accurate predictions and corresponding reasonable explanations?
â€¢ RQ2 Is SE-GNN robust to the structure noises in the datasets? â€¢ RQ3 How does each component of our proposed SE-GNN con-
tribute to the classification performance and explainability?
5.1 Datasets
To quantitatively and qualitatively evaluate SE-GNN in predictions and explanations, we conduct extensive experiments on three realworld datasets and two synthetic datasets. The statistics of the datasets are presented in Table 1.

